      "\n  rw [← proj_xy_eq_proj_xyL]\n  rw [show p.shift ∘ proj_xy = proj_xy ∘ p.innerOffsetPart from funext fun v ↦\n    by simp[MatrixPose.shift]; sorry]\n```\n\nWhen `funext fun v ↦ ...` is used to prove `p.shift ∘ proj_xy = proj_xy ∘ p.innerOffsetPart`, it introduces a variable `v` and sets up the goal:\n`⊢ (p.shift ∘ proj_xy) v = (proj_xy ∘ p.innerOffsetPart) v`\n\nThis goal is equivalent to:\n`⊢ p.shift (proj_xy v) = proj_xy (p.innerOffsetPart v)`\n\nLet's expand the left and right sides:\n- `p.shift (proj_xy v)`: `proj_xy v` is a vector in `Euc(3)`. `p` is a `MatrixPose`, so `p.shift` is a translation by `p.pos`. Thus, `p.shift w = w + p.pos` for any `w`. So, `p.shift (proj_xy v) = proj_xy v + p.pos`.\n- `proj_xy (p.innerOffsetPart v)`: `p.innerOffsetPart` is the inner offset part of `p`. From the definition of `MatrixPose`, `p.innerOffsetPart v = v - p.pos`. Then, `proj_xy` applied to this is `proj_xy (v - p.pos)`.\n\nSo the equality becomes:\n`⊢ proj_xy v + p.pos = proj_xy (v - p.pos)`\n\nThe `simp [MatrixPose.shift]` tactic simplifies `p.shift` to `fun w ↦ w + p.pos`.\nThe goal becomes:\n`⊢ (fun w ↦ w + p.pos) (proj_xy v) = proj_xy (p.innerOffsetPart v)`\nwhich simplifies to:\n`⊢ proj_xy v + p.pos = proj_xy (p.innerOffsetPart v)`\n\nThis is exactly the equality we need to prove. The `sorry` means this goal was not solved. The problem is that `simp` only simplifies `p.shift` but does not know how to simplify `p.innerOffsetPart` or `proj_xy` further in this context, and the equality `proj_xy v + p.pos = proj_xy (p.innerOffsetPart v)` is not trivial for `simp`.\n\nTo fix this, we need to expand `p.innerOffsetPart v` and `proj_xy` applied to it.\n\n`p.innerOffsetPart v` is `v - p.pos`.\nSo `proj_xy (p.innerOffsetPart v)` is `proj_xy (v - p.pos)`.\n`proj_xy w` is `⟨w.1, w.2, 0⟩` (if `w` is `⟨x, y, z⟩`, then `proj_xy w = ⟨x, y, 0⟩`).\n\nSo the goal is:\n`⊢ proj_xy v + p.pos = proj_xy (v - p.pos)`\n\nLet's write this out component-wise.\nLet `v = ⟨v₁, v₂, v₃⟩` a